# Generate some example data for clustering
tmp <- c(rnorm(30,-3), rnorm(30,3))
x <- cbind(x=tmp, y=rev(tmp))

plot(x)

Use the kmeans() function setting k to 2 and nstart=20

k <-  kmeans(x, centers = 2, nstart = 20)

Plot x colored by the kmeans cluster assignment and add cluster centers as blue points

palette(c("black", "red"))
plot (x, col=k$cluster)
points(k$centers, col="blue", pch =20, cex=2)

example #2: Step 1. Generate some example data for clustering

x <- rbind(
 matrix(rnorm(100, mean=0, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c1
 matrix(rnorm(100, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c2
 matrix(c(rnorm(50, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), # c3
 rnorm(50, mean = 0, sd = 0.3)), ncol = 2))
colnames(x) <- c("x", "y")

Step 2. Plot the data without clustering

plot(x)

Generate colors for known clusters (just so we can compare to hclust results)

col <- as.factor( rep(c("c1","c2","c3"), each=50) )

palette(c("red", "blue", "green"))
plot(x, col=col)

Use the dist(), hclust(), plot() and cutree() functions to return 2 and 3 clusters

d <- dist(x)
hc <- hclust(d)
plot(hc)

cluster2 <- cutree(hc, k=2)
table(cluster2, col)
##         col
## cluster2 c1 c2 c3
##        1 49  0  0
##        2  1 50 50
cluster3 <- cutree(hc, k=3)
table(cluster3, col)
##         col
## cluster3 c1 c2 c3
##        1 49  0  0
##        2  1  1 48
##        3  0 49  2
table(col, col)
##     col
## col  c1 c2 c3
##   c1 50  0  0
##   c2  0 50  0
##   c3  0  0 50

make up data

mydata <- matrix(nrow=100, ncol=10) 
rownames(mydata) <- paste("gene", 1:100, sep="") 
colnames(mydata) <- c( paste("wt", 1:5, sep=""),
 paste("ko", 1:5, sep="") ) 
for(i in 1:nrow(mydata)) {
 wt.values <- rpois(5, lambda=sample(x=10:1000, size=1))
 ko.values <- rpois(5, lambda=sample(x=10:1000, size=1))

 mydata[i,] <- c(wt.values, ko.values)
}
head(mydata)
##       wt1 wt2 wt3 wt4 wt5 ko1 ko2 ko3 ko4 ko5
## gene1 898 912 921 958 925 732 751 774 730 714
## gene2 127 148 138 143 165 877 849 907 909 848
## gene3 476 469 473 453 442 695 593 642 619 632
## gene4  49  42  35  31  35 144 135 123 113 121
## gene5  70  61  66  75  62 551 564 498 532 532
## gene6 159 127 138 149 150  47  68  68  63  58

do PCA

pca <- prcomp(t(mydata), scale=TRUE) 
#t() is to transpose data: flip columns to row, etc

plot pca in 2d plot

# x = pc1 and pc2
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2])

variance in pca

pca.var <- pca$sdev^2

#percent variance
pca.var.per <- round(pca.var/sum(pca.var)*100, 1) 
pca.var.per
##  [1] 90.4  2.1  2.0  1.9  1.3  0.7  0.6  0.5  0.4  0.0

barplot

barplot(pca.var.per, main="Scree Plot",
 xlab="Principal Component", ylab="Percent Variation")

according to scree plot, big difference btw the two groups along PC1 axis

make PC plot more useful/better to read

#create color vector
colvec <- colnames(mydata)
colvec[grep("wt", colvec)] <- "red"
colvec[grep("ko", colvec)] <- "blue"

#prettied plot
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], col=colvec, pch=16,
 xlab=paste0("PC1 (", pca.var.per[1], "%)"),
 ylab=paste0("PC2 (", pca.var.per[2], "%)"))
